{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "10 — The CLI API: Machine-Facing JSON Gateway",
  "description": "balaur's CLI is the machine-facing surface for external harnesses — LLM agents, scripts, CI pipelines. This tour covers the v1 envelope contract, the run() middleware, exit status ownership, the full command roster (19 commands across chat, tasks, knowledge, life, export, and infra), the determinism rule, and the balaur doctor preflight check.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/cli.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "10.1 — The gateway rule",
      "description": "The package comment states the fundamental contract:\n\n```go\n// Package cli is Balaur's machine-facing gateway: native subcommands on\n// the PocketBase root command, designed for external harnesses — including\n// LLM agents — that drive, inspect, seed, and verify a Balaur box without\n// scraping HTML. Every command prints one JSON envelope on stdout:\n//\n//  {\"v\":1,\"kind\":\"<command>.<subcommand>\",\"data\":<value>}\n```\n\nThe CLI is a **gateway**, not a reimplementation. Like the web gateway in `internal/web` (Tour 07), it adapts a delivery channel; it never re-implements capability. Every `balaur task list`, `balaur memory recall`, or `balaur chat` call reaches the same `internal/turn`, `internal/tasks`, `internal/knowledge`, and `internal/conversation` packages the web UI uses. The CLI only renders results as JSON instead of HTML.\n\nA bug fixed in `internal/tasks` is fixed for both surfaces without touching CLI code. The AGENTS.md invariant: **gateways adapt, they never re-implement**.\n\nTwo surface notes from the package comment:\n- **Deterministic by default**: only `chat` and `recap ensure` call a model. Every other command is a pure database read or write — safe to call from scripts, CI, or tests without a model configured.\n- **OS-access tools are not mirrored**: a shell already has the shell; the `BALAUR_OS_ACCESS` gate is about model reach, not owner reach."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/cli.go",
      "line": 53,
      "title": "10.2 — Register: the full command roster",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Register(app core.App, root *cobra.Command) {\n    root.AddCommand(\n        chatCmd(app),\n        taskCmd(app),\n        memoryCmd(app),\n        skillCmd(app),\n        noteCmd(app),\n        searchCmd(app),\n        lifeCmd(app),\n        journalCmd(app),\n        dayCmd(app),\n        recapCmd(app),\n        historyCmd(app),\n        auditCmd(app),\n        verifyCmd(app),\n        modelCmd(app),\n        selfCmd(app),\n        extCmd(app),\n        exportCmd(app),\n        doctorCmd(app),\n        seedCmd(app),\n    )\n}\n```\n\n`Register` mounts 19 top-level commands (some with subcommands) on the PocketBase root cobra command. They fall into four groups:\n\n- **Turn / inference**: `chat` (one turn), `recap` (summaries)\n- **Domain CRUD**: `task`, `memory`, `skill`, `note`, `search`, `life`, `journal`, `day`, `history`, `audit`\n- **Configuration / introspection**: `model`, `self`, `ext` (extensions)\n- **Infra / ops**: `export`, `doctor`, `seed`, `verify`\n\nEvery command is constructed by a dedicated function in its own file — `cli.go` holds only the envelope plumbing. This is the single registration point; `main.go` calls `cli.Register` once, after PocketBase boots."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/cli.go",
      "line": 105,
      "title": "10.3 — envelope: the v1 wire shape",
      "description": "```go\ntype envelope struct {\n    V    int    `json:\"v\"`\n    Kind string `json:\"kind\"`\n    Data any    `json:\"data\"`\n}\n\nfunc emit(w io.Writer, kind string, data any) error {\n    enc := json.NewEncoder(w)\n    enc.SetIndent(\"\", \"  \")\n    return enc.Encode(envelope{V: apiVersion, Kind: kind, Data: data})\n}\n```\n\nEvery command emits exactly one JSON object:\n- **`v`** — API version integer, currently `1` (`apiVersion` constant at line 39). Bumped only on breaking changes to the envelope shape or any command's `data` shape. Additive fields inside `data` are free without a bump.\n- **`kind`** — `<command>` or `<command>.<subcommand>` (e.g. `\"task.add\"`, `\"memory.recall\"`, `\"doctor\"`, `\"chat\"`). The discriminator for consumers switching on response type.\n- **`data`** — whatever the command emits; shape is command-specific.\n\n`json.SetIndent(\"\", \"  \")` makes output human-readable — the few extra bytes are irrelevant for harness I/O, and readable JSON is easier to debug.\n\nFailures write `{\"v\":1,\"kind\":\"error\",\"data\":{\"error\":\"...\"}}` to **stderr** and exit non-zero. Stdout stays clean — parsers can pipe stdout without filtering stderr."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/cli.go",
      "line": 84,
      "title": "10.4 — run: the command middleware",
      "description": "```go\nfunc run(app core.App, kind string, body func(cmd *cobra.Command, args []string) (any, error)) func(*cobra.Command, []string) error {\n    return func(cmd *cobra.Command, args []string) (err error) {\n        cmd.SilenceUsage = true\n        cmd.SilenceErrors = true\n        defer func() {\n            if r := recover(); r != nil {\n                err = failJSON(cmd, fmt.Errorf(\"panic: %v\", r))\n            }\n        }()\n        if mErr := app.RunAllMigrations(); mErr != nil {\n            return failJSON(cmd, fmt.Errorf(\"applying migrations: %w\", mErr))\n        }\n        out, bErr := body(cmd, args)\n        if bErr != nil {\n            return failJSON(cmd, bErr)\n        }\n        return emit(cmd.OutOrStdout(), kind, out)\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`run` is a higher-order function — the CLI equivalent of HTTP middleware. Every command body is wrapped by it. Three things it handles before every command:\n\n1. **Panic recovery** — any unhandled panic becomes a `{\"v\":1,\"kind\":\"error\",...}` JSON response rather than a stack trace on stderr. Harnesses get a structured error regardless.\n2. **Migration check** — `app.RunAllMigrations()` applies any pending migrations before the body runs. CLI commands must work on a fresh `--dir` that has never been `serve`d; PocketBase only auto-migrates in `serve` or `migrate` mode.\n3. **Uniform output** — success calls `emit` (stdout), failure calls `failJSON` (stderr + sets exit code).\n\n`SilenceUsage = true` prevents cobra from printing the usage message when a command returns an error — errors go through the JSON contract, not prose."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/cli.go",
      "line": 47,
      "title": "10.5 — exitCode: atomic exit status",
      "description": "```go\nvar exitCode atomic.Int32\n\nfunc ExitCode() int { return int(exitCode.Load()) }\n```\n\nPocketBase's `Execute()` discards `RunE` errors by design — the CLI owns its exit status. When a command fails, `failJSON` calls `exitCode.Store(1)`. After `app.Start()` returns, `main.go` reads the exit code:\n\n```go\nos.Exit(cli.ExitCode())\n```\n\n`atomic.Int32` is used because cobra commands may run on different goroutines in principle — the atomic ensures no data race even though in practice only one command runs per process invocation.\n\nExit code contract: `0` = success, `1` = any command failed. `balaur doctor` also sets the exit code to `1` when any **fatal** check fails, via a direct `exitCode.Store(1)` call in the doctor body — even though the doctor command itself does not return an error (it always emits valid JSON).\n\nThis is the only package-level mutable state in `internal/cli`. Everything else — the app, cobra command trees, flag values — is passed explicitly."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/chat.go",
      "line": 45,
      "title": "10.6 — chatCmd: the only model-calling command",
      "description": "```go\nfunc chatCmd(app core.App) *cobra.Command {\n    var timeout time.Duration\n    cmd := &cobra.Command{\n        Use:   \"chat <message>\",\n        Short: \"Run one real companion turn (model + tools) and report it as JSON\",\n        ...\n    }\n    cmd.RunE = run(app, \"chat\", func(cmd *cobra.Command, args []string) (any, error) {\n        client, err := chatClients(app)\n        ...\n        res, runErr := turn.Run(ctx, app, client, args[0], emit)\n        ...\n    })\n}\n```\n\n`chat` is the only command that calls the model (alongside `recap ensure`). It sends one owner message through `turn.Run` — the **same pipeline the web chatbar uses** (Tour 05). The JSON output carries:\n- **`reply`** — the assistant's final text\n- **`tools`** — every tool round (start + result), with `proposal` markers parsed out\n- **`claims_capture` / `capture_succeeded`** — the words-vs-deeds verdict (see `balaur verify`)\n- **`check_note`** — whether the runtime honesty check noted a mismatch\n- **`used_memories`** — memories recalled for context\n- **`messages_appended`** — how many rows were persisted\n\nThe `chatClients` var (line 22) is a package var so tests inject a fake `llm.Client` — tests never hit a real model (AGENTS.md). Outside `serve`, the CLI creates a Kronk engine on demand (`kronk.FromStore` or `kronk.NewEngine`) since the serve-time engine isn't running."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/task.go",
      "line": 51,
      "title": "10.7 — taskCmd: deterministic domain CRUD",
      "description": "```go\nfunc taskCmd(app core.App) *cobra.Command {\n    cmd := &cobra.Command{\n        Use:   \"task\",\n        Short: \"Manage commitments directly — deterministic, no model\",\n    }\n    cmd.AddCommand(taskAddCmd(app), taskListCmd(app), taskDoneCmd(app), taskSnoozeCmd(app), taskDropCmd(app))\n    return cmd\n}\n```\n\nThe `task` command group illustrates the pattern for all domain commands:\n- Five subcommands: `add`, `list`, `done`, `snooze`, `drop`\n- Every subcommand calls into `internal/tasks` (the domain package) directly — no turn pipeline, no model, no LLM round-trip\n- `taskJSON` (line 16) defines the stable output shape: `id`, `title`, `status`, `due`, `recur`, `snoozed_until`, etc., rendered through `jsonTime` for RFC3339-UTC timestamps\n\n`findTask` (line 42) shows how the CLI resolves a task ID: it looks up by ID in the `nodes` collection (tasks are a node type) and calls `tasks.Hydrate` to populate computed fields.\n\nThe same pattern applies to `memory`, `skill`, `note`, `search`, `life`, `journal`, `day`, `history`, and `audit` — each is a thin adapter over an existing domain package, rendered as JSON."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/knowledge.go",
      "line": 174,
      "title": "10.8 — memoryRecallCmd: mirrors the agent's recall path",
      "description": "```go\nfunc memoryRecallCmd(app core.App) *cobra.Command {\n```\n\n`memory recall` calls `knowledge.SearchActive` — the **same recall function the agent loop's recall tool uses** (`internal/tools/knowledge.go`) when assembling context for a turn: an FTS5 full-text query against the search sidecar, with a substring fallback. This matters for harnesses: **what `memory recall <query>` returns is evidence about what the model will actually be given**. One deliberate difference (see the code comment): unlike the model's recall tool, the CLI does not Touch the matched records, so a harness probing memory never skews the owner's usage statistics.\n\nThe `memory` command group (line 126) mounts seven subcommands: `propose`, `list`, `recall`, `edit`, plus the three lifecycle transitions (`approve`/`reject`/`archive`) generated by the shared `transitionCmd` helper (line 83).\n\nThe `transitionCmd` helper is a good example of the SUCKLESS rule applied to the CLI: `memory approve`, `memory reject`, `memory archive`, `skill approve`, `skill reject`, and `skill archive` all go through one shared function rather than duplicating the cobra boilerplate six times. Each calls `knowledge.Transition` in the domain package.\n\nSimilarly, `noteCmd` (line 300) and `searchCmd` (line 431) follow the same adapter pattern — the CLI is only responsible for parsing flags and shaping JSON output."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/verify.go",
      "line": 15,
      "title": "10.9 — verifyCmd: words vs deeds",
      "description": "```go\nfunc verifyCmd(app core.App) *cobra.Command {\n    cmd := &cobra.Command{\n        Use:   \"verify\",\n        Short: \"Words vs deeds for the last persisted turn — Balaur's honesty check, reusable by harnesses\",\n        ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`verify` reads the most recent persisted turn from the `messages` collection and runs the same words-vs-deeds check the runtime performs live after each turn. It reports:\n- **`claims_capture`** — did the reply promise to save something?\n- **`capture_succeeded`** — did a capture tool actually run without error?\n- **`honest`** — `!claims || captured` — the single boolean a harness can gate on\n- **`check_noted`** — was a mismatch noted by the runtime honesty checker?\n- **`turn`** — the full message rows of that turn, for inspection\n\nThis command is entirely **deterministic** — no model, no inference, pure database reads plus the `internal/verify` logic. It lets external harnesses and CI pipelines assert on Balaur's honesty without needing a model.\n\nThe `chat` command (step 10.6) returns the same `claims_capture` / `capture_succeeded` fields live; `verify` re-derives them from persistence — so you can check any prior turn, not just the most recent live one."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/export.go",
      "line": 25,
      "title": "10.10 — exportCmd: sovereign data out",
      "description": "```go\nfunc exportCmd(app core.App) *cobra.Command {\n    var out, archive string\n    var encrypt bool\n    ...\n    cmd.Flags().StringVar(&out, \"out\", \"\", \"destination directory (default: <data dir>/export)\")\n    cmd.Flags().BoolVar(&encrypt, \"encrypt\", false, \"encrypt the export into a single passphrase-protected archive\")\n    cmd.Flags().StringVar(&archive, \"archive\", \"\", \"output archive path (required with --encrypt)\")\n}\n```\n\n`export` is Balaur's sovereign-data-out surface (plans 192/194/195): a one-way, read-only Johnny Decimal Markdown mirror of every owner-authored active node, committed to a git history under the destination directory.\n\nTwo modes:\n- **Plain mirror** (`balaur export --out <dir>`): calls `export.ExportMirror` and reports `{\"files\": [...], \"dest\": \"<dir>\"}`\n- **Encrypted archive** (`balaur export --encrypt --archive <path>`): `runEncrypt` (line 60) renders the mirror into a throwaway temp dir, encrypts it with the passphrase from `$BALAUR_EXPORT_PASSPHRASE` (never a flag — so it does not appear in shell history), then wipes the temp dir with `defer os.RemoveAll(tmp)` so no plaintext copy is left behind.\n\nThe flag is named `--out` (not `--dir`) deliberately: `--dir` is a global PocketBase flag for the data directory, and colliding with it would be a hard-to-debug error (see plan 197).\n\nThe passphrase comes from an env var to avoid it landing in shell history alongside the command line — a small but deliberate security affordance."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/doctor.go",
      "line": 20,
      "title": "10.11 — doctor: preflight check for harnesses",
      "description": "```go\ntype doctorCheck struct {\n    Name   string `json:\"name\"`\n    OK     bool   `json:\"ok\"`\n    Detail string `json:\"detail\"`\n    Fatal  bool   `json:\"fatal\"`\n}\n```\n\n`balaur doctor` runs five checks and reports them as a JSON object. The `Fatal` flag is the key design decision:\n\n| Check | Fatal | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| `data_dir_writable` | yes | cannot serve if data dir is unwritable |\n| `collections_present` | yes | missing core collections means migrations didn't run |\n| `model_ready` | **no** | a box without a model is healthy but not chat-ready |\n| `os_access` | **no** | off is the expected default; informational |\n| `extensions` | **no** | zero approved extensions is fine |\n\nThe top-level `ok` is the AND of only the **fatal** checks. A harness should:\n1. Run `balaur --dir <path> doctor` and check exit code 0 to confirm the box is operable\n2. Inspect `data.checks` for `model_ready.ok` before issuing `chat` commands\n\n`doctorCheckers` (line 123) is a package-level `var` holding the check-list constructor — not hardcoded — so tests can inject an alternative list (e.g. a deliberately absent collection) without modifying production code. No model calls are made; `doctor` is safe to run at any time, including before the model is downloaded."
    }
  ]
}
